// Action-log replay determinism harness for the engine flow.
//
// This is a "record once, replay forever" fixture, distinct from
// test_full_game.mjs's live AI-driven determinism check: RECORDED_ACTIONS
// below is a frozen literal action log (not generated by calling the AI
// decision functions at test time), so this test stays valid even if a later
// patch changes AI tuning. It asserts two properties:
//
//   1. Replay purity: applying the same action list to a fresh state from the
//      same seed, twice, produces byte-identical final GameState objects (the
//      reducer is a pure function of (state, action) with no hidden mutable
//      state).
//   2. Fixture stability: replaying RECORDED_ACTIONS still reaches
//      EXPECTED_STATE_HASH, the hash pinned when this fixture was captured.
//      A change to the Action schema (renamed/added/removed fields on any
//      action variant) or to reducer behavior on this exact trace fails this
//      assertion loudly instead of silently drifting.
//
// versioned replay fixture -- regenerate RECORDED_ACTIONS and
// EXPECTED_STATE_HASH when the Action schema or auction semantics change:
// drive decideLandGrantAction/decideLandAuctionAction/decideDevelopAction/
// decideAuctionActions from REPLAY_SEED through applyAction (see
// tests/test_full_game.mjs's playFullGame for the scripting pattern) until
// the scoring phase, record every dispatched action into an array, and hash
// the final state with sha256(JSON.stringify(state)). Keep the one
// hand-injected assay_plot for player 0 at (0, 0) on the first develop turn
// (assay-flow coverage).
//
// Regenerated for M5: land_grant is now followed by a land_auction
// phase (0-3 colony plots per round, gated by LAND_AUCTION_COLONY_PROBABILITIES,
// each a bid_land/tick/end_land_auction sequence) before develop, and GameState
// gained a landMarket field -- so both the action stream and the reducer's
// randomness consumption differ from the prior fixture, which was regenerated
// in full by the scripting recipe above.
//
// Re-pinned for M6: the ACTION LOG is unchanged (personal and
// colony events fire automatically inside the reducer; no new action variant),
// but GameState gained the event fields (colonyEventSchedule, playerEventDeck,
// playerEventCursor, playerEventRngState, colonyEventRngState, eventHistory)
// and the fired events changed money/goods/board, so only EXPECTED_STATE_HASH
// was re-pinned. Event RNG is a derived sub-stream, so the core economy/auction
// randomness this log drives is byte-identical to the M5 fixture.
//
// Regenerated for M7: computeProduction now draws from the
// core `state.rngState` stream (a per-player Fisher-Yates shuffle plus one
// unconditional gaussian variance draw per owned, outfitted plot -- see
// economy.ts's computeProduction doc comment and docs/RULE_SOURCES.md,
// "Production: variance and the energy-shortfall model"), which this fixture's
// game never consumed before this patch (production previously never touched
// the RNG at all). That perturbs every later draw from the same stream --
// store pricing, land-auction rolls and pricing, and the colony-event
// tile/effect selections that thread through it -- so land-auction chain
// lengths and outcomes shift starting the first round production runs, and
// the recorded ACTION LOG itself changes shape (not just the hash) from this
// point on: the scripting recipe above was re-run in full (same REPLAY_SEED,
// same hand-injected assay_plot for player 0 at (0, 0) on their first develop
// turn), and both RECORDED_ACTIONS and EXPECTED_STATE_HASH were re-pinned.
//
// Regenerated (food-timer fix): the develop-phase food timer
// (`beginDevelopTurn` in turn.ts) was corrected from
// `FOOD_REQUIREMENTS_BY_ROUND[state.round - 1]` to
// `FOOD_REQUIREMENTS_BY_ROUND[min(state.round, 12)]` -- round 1 now consumes
// 3 food per player instead of the prior (incorrect) free round -- see
// docs/RULE_SOURCES.md, "Food requirement index: two offsets from one table".
// Food consumption itself does not draw from the RNG stream, but the changed
// tick budgets and AI money/food decisions from round 1 onward shift which
// actions the AI chooses (auction roles, buy/outfit/place timing), so the
// ACTION LOG changes shape starting the first round's auctions, not just the
// hash. The scripting recipe above was re-run in full (same REPLAY_SEED, same
// hand-injected assay_plot for player 0 at (0, 0) on their first develop
// turn), and both RECORDED_ACTIONS and EXPECTED_STATE_HASH were re-pinned.
//
// Re-pinned for M8: the ACTION LOG is unchanged (the wampus
// and pub-gambling subsystems draw from the new isolated `wampusRngState`
// stream and fire automatically/optionally inside the reducer; no existing
// action in this fixture triggers gamble or hunt_wampus), but GameState
// gained `wampusRngState`, DevelopPayload gained `wampus`, and Player gained
// `species` -- new serialized fields plus the wampus subsystem's own state
// advancing every develop-phase tick -- so only EXPECTED_STATE_HASH was
// re-pinned. Core economy/auction randomness this log drives is unaffected
// (wampus draws from its own isolated stream, matching planet_mule's own
// `Wampus` design), confirmed by the two other tests in this file (fixture
// stays reachable to the scoring phase and replays byte-identically).
//
// Regenerated for M9: scoring.ts's `computeScores` now values
// goods at the store's live `state.store.prices` (previously the static
// `STORE_BASE_PRICE` table) and adds each installed M.U.L.E.'s
// `POINTS_PER_MULE` plus outfit cost, not just flat land value. Mid-game
// callers of `computeScores` (`events.ts` `rankOrder`, used by develop-turn
// ordering; `land_auction.ts` `worstRanked`, used by colony-land-auction
// tie-breaks) pick up this corrected formula too, which changes tie-break
// outcomes as soon as store prices drift from their opening values or any
// M.U.L.E. is installed -- so the recorded ACTION LOG changes shape (not
// just the hash) from that point on. No colony failure fired on this replay
// (`payload.colonyFailed` is false; the fixture still runs the full 6
// rounds), so the M9 colony-failure/rating/First-Founder work did not by
// itself force a re-record, only the scoring-formula fix did. The scripting
// recipe above was re-run in full (same REPLAY_SEED, same hand-injected
// assay_plot for player 0 at (0, 0) on their first develop turn), and both
// RECORDED_ACTIONS and EXPECTED_STATE_HASH were re-pinned.
//
// Run via check_codebase.sh: node --import tsx --test tests/test_*.mjs
